Osprey Archeon 30 Pack

Description of the product

Made for hiking, commuting and traveling, the streamlined men’s Osprey Archeon 30 pack hauls your must-haves wherever the day takes you—from the natural world to the urban jungle.

Features

  • Front zipper access makes it easy to stash and retrieve your stuff
  • Constructed with Global Recycle Standard (GRS)-certified recycled materials and a C0 PFC-free durable water repellent (DWR) finish that sloughs off moisture
  • GRS ensures accurate content claims and good working conditions while minimizing harmful environmental and chemical impacts
  • Trail-specific additions include an internal reservoir sleeve, dual ice axe loops and webbing lash points; reservoir sleeve can fit up to a 3L reservoir (not included)
  • Included removable raincover keeps your gear dry if the weather turns
  • Dual-access side pockets secure your water bottles and snacks; dual low-profile, stretch-woven hipbelt stash pockets hold the small stuff
  • HDPE framesheet and dual profiled aluminum alloy stays spread the load across the entire back panel
  • Adjustable harness helps you get a perfect fit
  • Mesh-covered bumped foam allows for ventilation while keeping the load close to body

Question 2) Cooking Recipe

Buttermilk French Toast

Link of the recipe

https://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/buttermilk-french-toast-358115

Editor’s Note

This recipe was originally published in November 2008.

How the meal will look when it’s done

Buttermilk French Toast 1

Ingredients

Makes 4 Servings
  • 1 ½ cups well-shaken buttermilk
  • 4 large eggs
  • 3 tablespoons sugar
  • ¼ teaspoon salt
  • 12(½-inch-thick) slices challah (from a 1-pound loaf; not end slices)
  • 4 ½ tablespoons unsalted butter; divided

Accompaniment

  • Warm maple syrup

Cooking Steps

Step 1

Preheat oven to 200°F.

Step 2

Whisk together buttermilk, eggs, sugar, and salt in a bowl. Pour into a large 4-sided sheet pan, then add bread in 1 layer and soak, turning occasionally, until bread has absorbed all liquid but is not falling apart, about 20 minutes.

Step 3

Heat 1½ tablespoon butter in a 12-inch nonstick skillet over medium-high heat until foam subsides. Transfer 4 bread slices with a slotted spatula to skillet and cook, turning once, until slightly puffed and golden brown, about 3 minutes total. Transfer to a large shallow baking pan and keep warm in oven. Cook remaining bread in 2 batches, adding 1½ tablespoon butter between batches.

Question 3)Euclidean Distance

Definition [edit]

The Euclidean distance between points p and q is the length of the line segment connecting them (\(\overline{pq}\)).

In Cartesian coordinates, if p = (\(p_{1},p_{2},\dots,p_{n}\)) and q = (\(q_{1},q_{2},\dots,q_{n}\)) are two points in Euclidean n-space, then the distance (d) from p to q, or from q to p is given by the Pythagorean formula.

\(d\)(p,q) = \(d\)(q,p) = \(\sqrt{(q_{1}-p_{1})^2 + (q_{2}-p_{2})^2+\dots+(q_{n}-p_{n})^2} = \sqrt{\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{n}(q_{i}-p_{i})^2}\).

The position of a point in a Euclidean n-space is a Euclidean vector. So, p and q may be represented as Euclidean vectors, starting from the origin of the space (initial point) with their tips (terminal points) ending at the two points. The Euclidean norm, or Euclidean length, or magnitude of a vector measures the length of the vector.

\(\|p\| = \sqrt{p_1^2+p_2^2+\dots+p_n^2} = \sqrt{p.p}\),

where the last expression involves the dot product.
